Alstom, Hermes, LVMH, Renault, Schneider: French Equity Preview

-- B y   A l a n   K a t z
-- 
2011-05-31T06:03:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/alstom-hermes-lvmh-renault-schneider-french-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual changes in Paris. Symbols are in
parentheses after company names and prices are from the last
close.  France’s  CAC 40 Index (CAC)  fell 8.45 points, or 0.2 percent, to
3,942.53 in Paris. The broader SBF 120 Index declined 0.2
percent to 2,975.06 points.  Alstom SA (ALO)  : The world’s third-largest power-
equipment maker signed a memorandum of understanding for a $1.5
billion train project in Iraq, Salah Abdul-Razzaq, the governor
of Baghdad said. Alstom shares rose 54 cents, or 1.3 percent, to
41.89 euros.  Fimalac (FIM)  : The French financial-services company
said first-half net income rose 31 percent to 23.1 million
euros. The shares fell 61 cents, or 2.1 percent, to 27.90 euros.  Lafuma SA (LAF)  : The maker of Lafuma outdoor gear and
Oxbow surf wear said first-half net income was 0.7 million
euros, compared with a year-earlier loss of 2.5 million euros.
The shares fell 15 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 18.85 euros.  LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA (MC)  : The world’s
largest maker of luxury goods’ investment in  Hermes
International (RMS)  SCA is “peaceful” and not aggressive, Pierre
Gode, deputy chairman of LVMH said at a shareholders meeting of
Hermes International SCA. LVMH, which owns 20.2 percent of
Hermes, doesn’t intend to take control of Hermes, Gode said.
LVMH shares fell 35 cents, or 0.3 percent, to 118 euros. Hermes
shares fell 30 cents, or 0.2 percent, to 179 euros.  Naturex (NRX)  : The producer of natural vegetable
ingredients and extracts said first-quarter net income doubled
to 4.8 million euros. The stock rose 79 cents, 1.5 percent to
54.90 euros.  Renault SA (RNO)  : France’s second-biggest carmaker
appointed Carlos Tavares, a senior executive at Renault
affiliate Nissan Motor Co., to succeed Patrick Pelata as chief
operating officer and said the development of French production
sites will be “a priority.” The shares fell 28 cents, or 0.7
percent, to 38.79 euros.  Schneider Electric SA (SU)  : The electrical equipment
maker agreed to buy 74 percent of Luminous power Technologies
Pvt. Ltd, an India maker of inverters, critical power systems
and power storage systems for about 215 million euros. The
remaining 26 percent stake owned by the founders will be subject
to put and call options. Schneider shares rose 30 cents, or 0.3
percent, to 110.80 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Alan Katz  in Paris at   akatz5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Melissa Pozsgay at   mpozsgay@bloomberg.net . 